</h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Clinical_vs._non-clinical_mandatory_training_Navigating_the_essentials_for_healthcare_professionals_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1715938992" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Clinical_vs._non-clinical_mandatory_training_Navigating_the_essentials_for_healthcare_professionals_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1715938992 1536w" width="1766" height="1179" alt="Clinical vs. non-clinical mandatory training: Navigating the essentials for healthcare professionals - Dr Richard Dune -" title="Clinical vs. non-clinical mandatory training: Navigating the essentials for healthcare professionals - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-fbyfCU cCdixN pf-150_ pf-image-1"/><p class="sc-kHOZwM oQMan pf-151_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Image by LightFieldStudios Envato Elements</p><p class="sc-kHOZwM oQMan pf-153_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Clinical mandatory training refers to instruction necessary for clinical staff—those directly involved in delivering care to patients. This includes modules on basic life support, infection prevention, and handling medication, tailored to ensure that clinical personnel can provide safe and effective care.
<br><br>On the other hand, non-clinical mandatory training is designed for individuals who do not deliver direct care but support the healthcare environment. These modules might cover topics such as health and safety, fire safety, and data protection, crucial for maintaining a safe working environment.
